## Audit Policy and Status

The configured dependency license audit command is:

```bash
cargo deny check licenses
```

The same command is exposed through:

```bash
make license-audit
```

The committed `deny.toml` allows only explicitly listed permissive licenses and treats unknown, unlicensed, custom, non-commercial, GPL, AGPL, LGPL-only, MPL-only, EPL, and CDDL license expressions as blocked unless a future plan adds a documented review exception.

Current `Cargo.lock` license expressions pass the audit. Complex dual-license expressions are accepted only when the dependency metadata includes an allowed permissive branch. For example, `r-efi` includes `MIT OR Apache-2.0 OR LGPL-2.1-or-later`; the current audit accepts it through the MIT/Apache alternatives and does not treat the LGPL branch as selected.

Proprietary release artifacts remain blocked if the audit fails, if an unknown/copyleft dependency is introduced, or if this notice file no longer matches the bundled dependency set.
